data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.3+ supports **typed `DynamicData`** using `ValueTuple` instead of `object[]`, eliminating the untyped array:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — gives you compile-time type checking on the test data
- Array literals `["x", true]` → tuple literals `("x", true)`

This catches type mismatches at build time rather than runtime. Requires **MSTest 3.3+** (`Microsoft.Testing.Framework` or the updated `MSTest.TestFramework` NuGet package).
